<blockquote>
  <p>In recent years I begin, and nearly end, with Beckâ€™s rules of simple code. In priority order, simple code:<br />
â€¢ Runs all the tests;<br />
â€¢ Contains no duplication;<br />
â€¢ Expresses all the design ideas that are in the system;<br />
â€¢ Minimizes the number of entities such as classes, methods, functions, and the like.<br />
â€¦ Of these, I focus mostly on duplication. When the same thing is done over and over, itâ€™s a sign that there is an idea in our mind that is not well represented in the code. I try to figure out what it is. Then I try to express that idea more clearly.<br />
Expressiveness to me includes meaningful names, and I am likely to change the names of things several times before I settle inâ€¦. I also look at whether an object or method is doing more than one thing. If itâ€™s an object, it probably needs to be broken into two or more objects. If itâ€™s a method, I will always use the Extract Method refactoring on it, resulting in one method that says more clearly what it does, and some submethods saying how it is doneâ€¦</p>
